One thing missing from modern life is friendship between boys and old men. Tintin and Captain Haddock. My favorite Bulgarian book is about the author's childhood and the long summer journeys he undertook with a 70 year old friend of his from his village. Today it'd be impossible.

I've had older friends since high school and the dynamic of trading vigor and experience, the old man revitalized by the presence of youth, the young getting to skip over his age's natural dilemmas using the advice of the other, etc. strengthens both companions. It's wonderful.

He describes sleeping together in the open in a hay cart, looking at the stars and constellations and talking all night about life, him learning from his old friend's stories and anecdotes, having all sorts of adventures across the land while enjoying each other's company.

It's a relationship so powerful that tyrants feared it, because it was said to be the one thing that could bring them down. The spectre of pederasty ruins the possibility of friendship between boys and old men and is probably how culturally accepted sodomy harms society the most.

I think conceptualizing it merely as mentorship, male initiation, or any meme of this sort is selling it short. It has to be true friendship between equals. Not like the relation one has with his grandfather or an uncle, but a whole different kind. Tintin and Captain Haddock.
You get to collect your sharpest thoughts in one place and then read them together, it's almost a process of meditation and awakening in the Evolian sense
